[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] The **`EventSource`** interface is web content's interface to server-sent events.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] An `EventSource` instance opens a persistent connection to an HTTP server, which sends events in `text/event-stream` format.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] The connection remains open until closed by calling `EventSource.close()`.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] Once the connection is opened, incoming messages from the server are delivered to your code in the form of events.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] If there is an event field in the incoming message, the triggered event is the same as the event field value.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] If no event field is present, then a generic `message` event is fired.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] Unlike WebSockets, server-sent events are unidirectional; that is, data messages are delivered in one direction, from the server to the client (such as a user's web browser).
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] That makes them an excellent choice when there's no need to send data from the client to the server in message form.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] For example, `EventSource` is a useful approach for handling things like social media status updates, news feeds, or delivering data into a client-side storage mechanism like IndexedDB or web storage.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] Creates a new `EventSource` to handle receiving server-sent events from a specified URL, optionally in credentials mode.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] A number representing the state of the connection.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] A string representing the URL of the source.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] A boolean value indicating whether the `EventSource` object was instantiated with cross-origin (CORS) credentials set (`true`), or not (`false`, the default).
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] Closes the connection, if any, and sets the `readyState` attribute to `CLOSED`.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] If the connection is already closed, the method does nothing.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] Fired when a connection to an event source failed to open.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] Fired when data is received from an event source.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] Fired when a connection to an event source has opened.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] Additionally, the event source itself may send messages with an event field, which will create ad hoc events keyed to that value.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] In this basic example, an `EventSource` is created to receive unnamed events from the server; a page with the name `sse.php` is responsible for generating the events.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] Each received event causes our `EventSource` object's `onmessage` event handler to be run.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] It, in turn, creates a new `<li>` element and writes the message's data into it, then appends the new element to the list element already in the document.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-eventsource] To listen to named events, you'll require a listener for each type of event sent.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-websocket] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-websocket] The `WebSocket` object provides the API for creating and managing a WebSocket connection to a server, as well as for sending and receiving data on the connection.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-websocket] To construct a `WebSocket`, use the `WebSocket()` constructor.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-websocket] Returns a newly created `WebSocket` object.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-websocket] The binary data type used by the connection.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-websocket] The sub-protocol selected by the server.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-websocket] Listen to these events using `addEventListener()` or by assigning an event listener to the `oneventname` property of this interface.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-websocket] Fired when a connection with a `WebSocket` is closed.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-websocket] Fired when a connection with a `WebSocket` has been closed because of an error, such as when some data couldn't be sent.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-websocket] Also available via the `onerror` property.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-websocket] Fired when data is received through a `WebSocket`.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-websocket] Also available via the `onmessage` property.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-websocket] Fired when a connection with a `WebSocket` is opened.
[src:socket-io-realtime/api-websocket] Also available via the `onopen` property.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] In software architecture, the **publish–subscribe pattern** (**pub/sub**) is a messaging pattern in which message senders, called **publishers**, categorize messages into classes (or *topics*), and send them without needing to know which components will receive them.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Message recipients, called **subscribers**, express interest in one or more classes and only receive messages in those classes, without needing to know the identity of the publishers.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern decouples the components that produce messages from those that consume them, and supports asynchronous, many-to-many communication.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] The publish–subscribe model is commonly contrasted with message queue-based and point-to-point messaging models, where producers send messages directly to consumers.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publish–subscribe is a sibling of the message queue paradigm, and is typically a component of larger message-oriented middleware systems.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many modern messaging frameworks and protocols, such as the Java Message Service (JMS), Apache Kafka, and MQTT, support both the pub/sub and queue-based models.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] This pattern provides greater network scalability and supports more dynamic topologies, but can make it harder to modify the publisher’s logic or the structure of the published data.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Compared to synchronous patterns like RPC and point-to-point messaging, publish–subscribe provides the highest level of decoupling among architectural components.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, it can also lead to semantic or format coupling between publishers and subscribers, which may cause systems to become entangled or brittle over time.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] In publish–subscribe systems, subscribers typically receive only a subset of messages.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] In most pub/sub systems, publishers and subscribers communicate through a central intermediary such as a message broker or event bus.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] The broker receives messages from publishers and forwards them to the appropriate subscribers, optionally performing store and forward, priority queuing, or other routing logic.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Some pub/sub systems use **brokerless** architectures, in which publishers and subscribers discover each other and exchange messages directly.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, the Data Distribution Service (DDS) middleware uses IP multicast and metadata sharing to establish communication paths.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokerless systems require construction of overlay networks, often using Small-World topologies to enable efficient routing.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] It was shown by Jon Kleinberg that efficient decentralized routing requires Navigable Small-World topologies, which are employed in federated or peer-to-peer pub/sub systems.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Locality-aware pub/sub networks use low-latency links to reduce message propagation time.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] One of the earliest publicly described pub/sub systems was the "news" subsystem of the Isis Toolkit, presented at the 1987 ACM Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP '87).
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] As distributed systems became more common, the publish–subscribe model evolved to emphasize asynchronous messaging and broker-mediated communication, setting it apart from the more tightly coupled observer pattern.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Publishers are loosely coupled to subscribers, and need not even know of their existence.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] With the topic being the focus, publishers and subscribers are allowed to remain ignorant of system topology.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Each can continue to operate as per normal independently of the other.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] In the traditional tightly coupled client–server paradigm, the client cannot post messages to the server while the server process is not running, nor can the server receive messages unless the client is running.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Many pub/sub systems decouple not only the locations of the publishers and subscribers but also decouple them temporally.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] A common strategy used by middleware analysts with such pub/sub systems is to take down a publisher to allow the subscriber to work through the backlog (a form of bandwidth throttling).
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Pub/sub provides the opportunity for better scalability than traditional client-server, through parallel operation, message caching, tree-based or network-based routing, etc.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Outside of the enterprise environment, on the other hand, the pub/sub paradigm has proven its scalability to volumes far beyond those of a single data center, providing Internet-wide distributed messaging through web syndication protocols such as RSS and Atom.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] These syndication protocols accept higher latency and lack of delivery guarantees in exchange for the ability for even a low-end web server to syndicate messages to (potentially) millions of separate subscriber nodes.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Redundant subscribers in a pub/sub system can help assure message delivery with minimal additional complexity.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] For example, a factory may utilize a pub/sub system where equipment can publish problems or failures to a subscriber that displays and logs those problems.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] If the logger fails (crashes), equipment problem publishers won't necessarily receive notice of the logger failure, and error messages will not be displayed or recorded by any equipment on the pub/sub system.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a client/server system, when an error logger fails, the system will receive an indication of the error logger (server) failure.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, the client/server system will have to deal with that failure by having redundant logging servers online, or by dynamically spawning fallback logging servers.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] This adds complexity to the client and server designs, as well as to the client/server architecture as a whole.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] In a pub/sub system, redundant logging subscribers that are exact duplicates of the existing logger can be added to the system to increase logging reliability without any impact to any other equipment on the system.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] The feature of assured error message logging can also be added incrementally, subsequent to implementing the basic functionality of equipment problem message logging.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] The most serious problems with pub/sub systems are a side-effect of their main advantage: the decoupling of publisher from subscriber.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] A pub/sub system must be designed carefully to be able to provide stronger system properties that a particular application might require, such as assured delivery.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] The pub/sub pattern scales well for small networks with a small number of publisher and subscriber nodes and low message volume.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] However, as the number of nodes and messages grows, the likelihood of instabilities increases, limiting the maximum scalability of a pub/sub network.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] For pub/sub systems that use brokers (servers), the argument for a broker to send messages to a subscriber is in-band, and can be subject to security problems.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers might be fooled into sending notifications to the wrong client, amplifying denial of service requests against the client.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Brokers themselves could be overloaded as they allocate resources to track created subscriptions.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Even with systems that do not rely on brokers, a subscriber might be able to receive data that it is not authorized to receive.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] An unauthorized publisher may be able to introduce incorrect or damaging messages into the pub/sub system.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] This is especially true with systems that broadcast or multicast their messages.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS)) can prevent unauthorized access, but cannot prevent damaging messages from being introduced by authorized publishers.
[src:socket-io-realtime/publish-subscribe-pattern] Architectures other than pub/sub, such as client/server systems, are also vulnerable to authorized message senders that behave maliciously.
[src:socket-io-realtime/server-sent-events] All modern browsers support server-sent events: Firefox 6+, Google Chrome 6+, Opera 11.5+, Safari 5+, Microsoft Edge 79+, Brave.
[src:socket-io-realtime/server-sent-events] Since SSE does not use either persistent connections nor chunked transfer encoding, HTTP/1.1 is not a technical requirement.
[src:socket-io-realtime/server-sent-events] The SSE mechanism was first specified by Ian Hickson as part of the "WHATWG Web Applications 1.0" proposal starting in 2004.
[src:socket-io-realtime/server-sent-events] In September 2006, the Opera web browser implemented the experimental technology in a feature called "Server-Sent Events".
[src:socket-io-realtime/server-sent-events] The W3C published Server-Sent Events as a Recommendation on February 3, 2015, after years of development through Working Drafts and Candidate Recommendations.
[src:socket-io-realtime/server-sent-events] When sending high-frequency data , the server must manage backpressure to prevent saturating clients.
[src:socket-io-realtime/socket-io] Socket.IO is also a protocol, where different complying implementations of the protocol can communicate with each other.
[src:socket-io-realtime/socket-io] The main implementation consists of two parts: a client that runs in the browser and a server for Node.js.
[src:socket-io-realtime/socket-io] Apart from the main implementation, there are multiple implementations, for example, the official Deno (JavaScript), C++, Java, Python, and Swift servers.
[src:socket-io-realtime/socket-io] Socket.IO primarily uses the WebSocket protocol with polling as a fallback option, while providing the same interface.
[src:socket-io-realtime/socket-io] Although it can be used simply as a wrapper for WebSockets, it provides many additional features such as heartbeats and timeouts.
[src:socket-io-realtime/socket-io] It can be installed with the npm (Node Package Manager).
[src:socket-io-realtime/socketio-socket-io] Our issues list is exclusively reserved for bug reports and feature requests.
[src:socket-io-realtime/socketio-socket-io] If you think that you have found a security vulnerability in our project, please do not create an issue in this GitHub repository, but rather refer to our Security Policy.
[src:socket-io-realtime/socketio-socket-io] Please make sure to read our Contributing Guide before creating an issue or making a pull request.
[src:socket-io-realtime/socketio-socket-io] Thanks to everyone who has already contributed to Socket.IO!
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] If you are new to Socket.IO, we recommend checking out our tutorial.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] Socket.IO is a library that enables **low-latency**, **bidirectional** and **event-based** communication between a client and a server.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] You can find more details about that in the "How it works" section.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] Socket.IO is **NOT** a WebSocket implementation.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] Although Socket.IO indeed uses WebSocket for transport when possible, it adds additional metadata to each packet.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] That is why a WebSocket client will not be able to successfully connect to a Socket.IO server, and a Socket.IO client will not be able to connect to a plain WebSocket server either.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] If you are looking for a plain WebSocket server, please take a look at ws or µWebSockets.js.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] There are also discussions for including a WebSocket server in the Node.js core.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] On the client-side, you might be interested in the robust-websocket package.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] Socket.IO is not meant to be used in a background service for mobile applications.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] The Socket.IO library keeps an open TCP connection to the server, which may result in a high battery drain for your users.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] Please use a dedicated messaging platform like FCM for this use case.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] The connection will fall back to HTTP long-polling in case the WebSocket connection cannot be established.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] This feature was the #1 reason people used Socket.IO when the project was created more than ten years ago (!), as the browser support for WebSockets was still in its infancy.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] Even if most browsers now support WebSockets (more than 97%), it is still a great feature as we still receive reports from users that cannot establish a WebSocket connection because they are behind some misconfigured proxy.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] Under some particular conditions, the WebSocket connection between the server and the client can be interrupted with both sides being unaware of the broken state of the link.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] That's why Socket.IO includes a heartbeat mechanism, which periodically checks the status of the connection.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] And when the client eventually gets disconnected, it automatically reconnects with an exponential back-off delay, in order not to overwhelm the server.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] The packets are automatically buffered when the client is disconnected, and will be sent upon reconnection.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] This also works when scaling to multiple nodes.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] Namespaces allow you to split the logic of your application over a single shared connection.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] This can be useful for example if you want to create an "admin" channel that only authorized users can join.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] That's a fair question, since WebSockets are supported almost everywhere now.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] That being said, we believe that, if you use plain WebSockets for your application, you will eventually need to implement most of the features that are already included (and battle-tested) in Socket.IO, like reconnection, acknowledgements or broadcasting.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] So, a few additional bytes for each message, which can be further reduced by the usage of a custom parser.
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] The size of the browser bundle itself is `10.4 kB` (minified and gzipped).
[src:socket-io-realtime/v4] You can find the details of the Socket.IO protocol here.
